TERRAFORM WORKFLOW : Write > Initialize > Plan > Apply
Terraform init : it prepares the env to run the terraform commands. Downloads required providers(aws, azure, etc) and modules used in the terraform conf.
                 also configures the backend for storing tf state and creates the lock file.
                 We have to use it at the start of new project or time you addd, remove or upgrade providers/modules or change the backend settings in your conf.
Terraform lock file : Everytime you run terraform init . Terraform creates or updates a file called .terraform.lock.hcl. in your working dir.
                lock dependency versions for consistency across env.
                Commit to version control and managed automatically by terraform.
.terraform directory : to store the project providers and modules. .terraform/providers directory stores cached versions of the config providers.
                       .terraform/modules directory stores downloaded versions of any referenced modules.

Q1 . Should .terraform dir be in Version control ? 
Ans: NO, add to your .gitignore file. Contains easily recreatable files. Can be large in size and contain platform specific files.

Q2. Can u delete the .terraform dir ?
Ans: Technically YES. Run terraform init to create it again. Useful for troubleshooting or cleaning up old dependencies.

Terraform PLAN : generates execution plan showing the changes that terraform will make to the real-world.
                  It gives u the ability to perform a dry-run.
Saving a Plan : the exact actions in the saved plan will be executed, no surprise.
                Save plan, have it reviewed, then apply later with confidence.
                $terraform plan -out=myplan.tfplan or filename.tf or etc  (filename can be anything)
Q3. How to apply a saved plan ? 
Ans: $terraform apply myplan.tfplan
-----------------------------------
RESOURCE GRAPH:
Terraform automatically builds a dependency graph from your conf to determine the order in which to create, update or destroy resources.
- Resource order in your .tf files doesn't matter
- Resource graph is how terraform achieves parallel execution.
- Foundation for understanding resource dependencies.

DEPENDENCIES : 
Two type of dependencies : 
Implicit dependencies(auto) : a reference to another resource that terraform already knows about.
Explicit : Used when there's a dependencies that terraform can't automatically detect from resource references alone. Use "depends_on" for create an
           explicit dependency.
PARALLEL RESOURCE OPERATION : 
-  Terraform processes the graph with parallel execution. processes nodes as soon as their dependencies are satisfied. Non-
dependent resources are created/modified simultaneously.
-  Default config: Terraform manages 10 operations in parallel but can be modified using the -parallelism flag
                    $terraform apply -parallelism=5
                    When to change parallelism : if u r running into API rate limiting issue or for debugging purposes.
                    
Terraform Apply : it make changes to your infra.
                  Terraform apply runs a plan first to compare your exisiting infra to your desired state. By default, terr
                  aform will prompt u to proceed with the proposed changes.
          *STATE LOCKING :   terraform locks the state file during apply to prevent concurrent modifications.
          *STATE UPDATES : State file is updated after each resource is successfully created/modified/destroyed.
          *NO AUTOMATIC ROLLBACK : If a resrc fails during apply, terraform does not rollback previous successful changes.They 
                                  remain in place.
          *RESPECTS DEPENDENCIES : Commit to version control and managed automatically by terraform.


            $terraform apply
            $terraform apply myplan.tfplan
            $terraform apply -auto-approve

            
















